  {
    "content": "The correct order of acidity for the following compounds is :<br><br><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1l1dx6yz7/cb476b3a-cf8a-4b46-b04a-ceed7315605a/d4ea5e30-b059-11ec-8ab2-cf6ddca41d3b/file-1l1dx6yz8.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1l1dx6yz7/cb476b3a-cf8a-4b46-b04a-ceed7315605a/d4ea5e30-b059-11ec-8ab2-cf6ddca41d3b/file-1l1dx6yz8.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;max-height: 50vh\" alt=\"WB JEE 2020 Chemistry - General Organic Chemistry Question 19 English\">",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "II &lt; IV &lt; III &lt; I"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "II &lt; III &lt; I &lt; IV"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "II &lt; III &lt; IV &lt; I "
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "III &lt; II &lt; I &lt; IV"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "B"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "Among the given compounds, compound IV is a carboxylic acid whereas rest are phenols. Carboxylic acids are more acidic than phenol due to more stability of carboxylate ion than phenoxide ion. So, compound IV is the most acidic among the given compounds.<br><br>Further, acidity of phenols increases by the presence of electron withdrawing groups (EWG) such as $$ - $$\nNO<sub>2</sub>. The effect of EWG is more pronounced at ortho- and para-positions than at m-position due to combined effect of $$ - $$\nI and $$ - $$\nR effect of $$ - $$\nNO<sub>2</sub> group at p-position. On the other hand, electron donating group (EDG) such as $$ - $$\nCH<sub>3</sub> decreases the acidity of phenols.<br><br>Therefore, the correct order of acidity is as follows :<br><br><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1l1dx89dt/23eb4696-bb77-4d8e-9d3c-9fe9f2c40a5d/f8c34f10-b059-11ec-8ab2-cf6ddca41d3b/file-1l1dx89du.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1l1dx89dt/23eb4696-bb77-4d8e-9d3c-9fe9f2c40a5d/f8c34f10-b059-11ec-8ab2-cf6ddca41d3b/file-1l1dx89du.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;max-height: 50vh\" alt=\"WB JEE 2020 Chemistry - General Organic Chemistry Question 19 English Explanation\">",
    "topic": null,
    "year": 2020,
    "yearKey": "wb-jee-2020",
    "difficulty": null
  },
  {
    "content": "For the following carbocations, the correct order of stability is <br><br>I. $$^ \\oplus C{H_2} - COC{H_3}$$<br><br>II. $$^ \\oplus C{H_2} - OC{H_3}$$<br><br>III. $$^ \\oplus C{H_2} - C{H_3}$$",
    "options": [
      {
        "identifier": "A",
        "content": "III &lt; II &lt; I"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "B",
        "content": "II &lt; I &lt; III"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "C",
        "content": "I &lt; II &lt; III"
      },
      {
        "identifier": "D",
        "content": "I &lt; III &lt; II"
      }
    ],
    "correct_options": [
      "D"
    ],
    "answer": null,
    "explanation": "Carbocations are stabilised by the presence of electron donating group (+ R, + I, + H) and destabilised by presence of electron withdrawing group ($$ - $$R, $$ - $$H, $$ - $$I).<br><br><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1l1dxaj9x/0db63e21-64f1-458f-a1aa-dd045e85ec25/3805c450-b05a-11ec-8ab2-cf6ddca41d3b/file-1l1dxaj9y.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1l1dxaj9x/0db63e21-64f1-458f-a1aa-dd045e85ec25/3805c450-b05a-11ec-8ab2-cf6ddca41d3b/file-1l1dxaj9y.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width: 100%;height: auto;display: block;margin: 0 auto;max-height: 50vh\" alt=\"WB JEE 2020 Chemistry - General Organic Chemistry Question 20 English Explanation 1\"><br><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1l1dxbeal/d76f97ff-1bb8-465a-a8d2-eb83d665a24a/4ffbccd0-b05a-11ec-8ab2-cf6ddca41d3b/file-1l1dxbeam.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1l1dxbeal/d76f97ff-1bb8-465a-a8d2-eb83d665a24a/4ffbccd0-b05a-11ec-8ab2-cf6ddca41d3b/file-1l1dxbeam.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh\" alt=\"WB JEE 2020 Chemistry - General Organic Chemistry Question 20 English Explanation 2\"><br>It is stabilised by + R-effect. So, it is the most stable carbocation.<br><br>III. $$\\mathop C\\limits^ +  {H_2} - C{H_3}$$<br><br>Hyperconjugation of $$ - C{H_3}$$ group stabilises the ion to some extent but not as effective as $$ - OC{H_3}$$.<br><br>Therefore, its stability is intermediate between I and II.<br><br>Hence, the correct order of stability of carbocations is II &gt; III &gt; I.<br><br>So, the correct option is (d).",
    "topic": null,
